# Agent Engine Patterns

## Provider Abstraction

- Always use Vercel AI SDK provider wrappers (`@ai-sdk/anthropic`, `@ai-sdk/amazon-bedrock`)
- Never import `@anthropic-ai/sdk` or call Anthropic API directly
- Provider selection is driven by channel config, with environment fallback

## Tool Definition

- Define tools with `tool()` from the `ai` package
- Use Zod schemas for parameter validation
- Tool `execute` functions must be async and return serializable data
- Tag tools with `requiresApproval: true` metadata when they perform destructive actions

## MCP Integration

- Acquire tools via `MCPManager.getToolsForChannel()`
- Merge MCP tools with native tools (memory_save, memory_search, memory_list)
- Apply tool policies (allow/deny lists) before passing to `generateText`

## Agent Loop

- Use `generateText({ maxSteps })` for controllable multi-step execution
- Default `maxSteps: 10` (configurable per channel)
- Always inject relevant memories into system prompt before agent loop
- Always run guardrails pre-processing before and post-processing after

## Sub-Agent Delegation

- Use `spawnSubtask()` for parallel background tasks
- Sub-agents get isolated `generateText` calls with filtered tools
- Results stored in Valkey keyed by task ID
- Main agent retrieves results via `getSubtaskResult()`

## Cost Tracking

- After every `generateText` call, extract `usage.promptTokens` and `usage.completionTokens`
- Log to `usage_logs` table via `CostTracker`
- Calculate estimated cost using `MODEL_PRICING` from `@personalclaw/shared`

## Memory Integration

- Before building system prompt, call memory engine for top-N relevant memories
- Agent has access to `memory_save`, `memory_search`, `memory_list` tools
- After conversation, persist to Tier 1 (Valkey) and Tier 2 (Postgres)
- Check for compaction threshold and trigger memory flush if needed
